            Snapshot        


Building a better anti-microbial

Poly Group believes its Nouvex, based on Purdue research, can be a game-changer




Nov 13, 2015, 6:00am EST









David Serchuk


                            Reporter                        

Louisville Business First














                    Share
                


























 Order Reprints


 Save Article




 Print
















 



 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Twitter




 Save Article





More 






 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Order Reprints




 Twitter




 Save Article
























 







David Serchuk


                            Reporter                        

Louisville Business First









 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    French Country Home has Fabulous Curb Appeal & an Amazing Interior                




See All Homes of the Day





 











 Enlarge





                Poly Group COO Craig Kalmer, left, and chief scientific officer Thomas Hopkins, say the… more 

                William DeShazer            








 



Poly Group LLC is betting that if it licenses a better anti-microbial product, the world will beat a path to its door.
The company was formed in 2010 by Jack Haywood and Doug Hamilton, who earlier had begun working with anti-microbials at their company, Pro Laminators in Sellersburg.













 Enlarge






                            Poly Group COO Craig Kalmer, left, and chief scientific officer Thomas Hopkins, say the… more 
William DeShazer










 


They eventually sought to improve their process by pairing up with Jeffrey Youngblood, an associate professor at Purdue University’s School of Materials Engineering in West Lafayette, Ind.
Youngblood had created an innovation known as a hydrophilized bactericidal polymer technology.
Poly Group exists to commercialize that research, and the product currently goes by the commercial name of Nouvex.
The company is located in the Purdue Research Park of Southeast Indiana in New Albany.
Wide applications
Nouvex investors — about 60 people have contributed about $3 million since 2010 — believe the product could be a game-changing anti-bacterial and anti-viral product.
Craig Kalmer, chief operating officer at Poly Group, said it kills 99.9 of most bacteria it contacts, and it does so in about one to 10 minutes.
Nouvex’s formulation allows it to become part of a product.
Paper or plastic could be infused with Nouvex, and it can be mixed into the durable coatings applied to things such as doorknobs, where it will fight bacteria as long as the coating lasts.





Plastic laminates can have Nouvex infused throughout, as can floors.
Kalmer thinks the applications are limitless, including a possible health care use. Urinary catheters, which often cause problems for patients because of bacterial buildup, can have Nouvex added.
Massive market
Kalmer said Poly Group is awaiting approval from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency before it can begin officially selling and licensing Nouvex. That result is expected anytime before August.
Purdue University owns the patent on the product, and the Poly Group has the exclusive license to take the technology to market.
Kalmer said the anti-microbial additives market is a $6 billion to $7 billion industry, which leads Nouvex investors to believe it could deliver huge returns on their investments. “Our goal is that within the next five years, we get about 10 percent of that,” he said.

New product
One reason for Kalmer’s optimism is that Nouvex can be added easily to products that already have made it to the market. “It’s going to be a lower-cost, better alternative to what’s out there today,” he said.
And there seems to be no direct competition. Kalmer said the EPA considers Nouvex a “brand-new entity.”
Business First asked Kalmer whether he had any concerns that Nouvex could draw challenges over potential vulnerabilities.
For example, the anti-bacterial triclosan, which is widely used in hand soap and toothpaste, has drawn the interest of the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.




 


While emphasizing that further study is needed, the agency said that studies raise the possibility that triclosan contributes to making bacteria resistant to antibiotics.
Kalmer said Nouvex works differently, attacking bacteria in a way that bleach would, damaging the bacteria’s cell walls. Antibiotics, meanwhile, penetrate into bacteria, which can develop a sort of “pump” mechanism that allows it to expunge the chemical.
This won’t happen with Nouvex, he said, and the company believes this eliminates the possibility of super-bugs.
“Nouvex doesn’t have to go into the cell in order to kill it,” he said. “Based on our testing, we do not cause any sort of mutation in the organization, so we do not anticipate that being an issue.”

About Poly Group LLC
Business: The company has developed an anti-microbial called Nouvex
Founded: 2010
Address: 3000 Technology Ave., Suite N2221, New Albany
Website: www.polygroupllc.net
Employees: Two — Craig Kalmer, chief operations officer, and Thomas A. Hopkins, chief scientific officer
Financing:$3 million in investment from about 60 investors. The company has no sales yet, as its signature product, Nouvex, is awaiting EPA approval.

One of a kind
Poly Group’s signature product, Nouvex, is a category unto itself, according to chief operations officer Craig Kalmer.
When Kalmer submitted Nouvex’s information to the EPA for approval, he said, the agency categorized Nouvex as “a brand new entity.”
The government, he said, had never seen anything quite like it before.












 






